These tattoos and their stories are how I’m making sense of what life gave me. They are a physical manifestation of my ideals after I spent most of my life being told to believe in the invisible.

I grew up in a cult, and was violently ejected from it as a teen. There has been a massive void left in how I view the world and make sense of complex things. Does it matter that stories from video games have given me comfort and meaning? Are they any less significant?

I hate this feeling of needing to explain or rationalize to other people what certain tattoos mean to me. I’m getting a tattoo this weekend that I’ve wanted since I was a teen and yeah, sure it’s from a video game, but the story means much to me.

All this is why ARTPOP will always mean the universe to me. Thanks Gaga, this little gay really appreciated it. ❤️

Having my first car and that album, after years of being shackled to my parents views of who and what I should be, I felt utterly free. I could feel that Gaga poured her soul into that album, and I really feel it helped save my life.

Of course, after finding it, my parents immediately confiscated it. At that moment, it became my symbol of resistance. I was tired of being pushed down, or told that “I was acting too gay”. A few days later I stole it back, and for months it was the only album I listened to.

As the weeks went by, I became braver and more confident in my identity and self. One day at the mall, I saw ARTPOP, and I knew I needed it. It was the first Gaga album I bought. It really was the first non-religious album I bought as well.

Early 2014, my parents tried putting me through conversion therapy. I was faced with a choice. Suppress my entire identity to stay safe in the church, or embrace myself and lose everyone. I eventually chose to embrace myself, and actively opposed my parents.

After being forced out of the closet late 2013, things got really rough for a while. My whole life and identity was in a crisis, and I was teetering on the edge of losing every person I knew and grew up with. I was depressed and suicidal.

Story time! Ever since I first heard her on the radio, I was enamoured with @ladygaga Something about her music made my gay little heart happy. Unfortunately, due to my parents/friends religious convictions, I didn’t dare openly listen to her music with them around.
